Just a bit of a Komodo X update. We are working as fast as we can to fulfill all stormtrooper KX orders, building testing and getting them out the door as quick as possible. We hope to have 90% of the orders shipped out this upcoming week and the remaining the week after. For anyone wanting to see what the black cameras look like in real life , we have some pre production Komodo X black cameras that we assembled for our internal team testing and we will loan these few to our partners booths for Cinegear, so you can find them on the floor and take a peek, and no you can’t buy them. The black production cameras won’t start their build process till mid June, with shipping targeted for the last week of June. I have had lots of questions from eager purchasers wondering why we can’t go any faster, and unfortunately it is way more complicated than it would appear. Apart from a ton of supply chain planning ( which we got wrong ) it is all about the new sensors like it almost always is, we can make only so many so quickly.. it’s a bit of an art form and the yield is always low at the start of production and if we push too hard to fast things break. The black Komodo-X, or more accurately the actual “ official “ launch of Komodo-X is this Wednesday the 31st, and everything on our website and dealers website will be changed to displaying only black cameras and will start officially taking preorders for the black cameras then. We will also have an official livestream at some time on the 31st as well with Cleigh and Jonny and myself going through the camera and will have some time at the end to answer any questions.

Join RED for REDTech Live May 31 at 12PM PST as Jarred, Cleigh, and the RED team formally introduce KOMODO-X reviewing the product development, new sensor technology, accessories, and live Q&A. Tune in May 31 at 12PM PST.

Just a little public service announcement about Cfexpress readers since we have gotten an inrush of questions looking for some clarity and support as there seems to currently be quite a few very bad readers on amazon that won’t necessarily harm your card but it just won’t show up,  or almost worse they go very very very very slow.  CFexpress card readers and the USB/Thunderbolt protocols they use have a lot of weird nuances. RED/Angelbird CFexpress cards ( and most other pro level CFexpress cards ) all surpass the bandwidth of some versions of USB3 or USB4  so when you choose a reader look for a Gbps number.. it should be 20Gbps or higher.  If it doesn’t have that number it’s probably slow.  Just because it says USB4 or USB 3.2 doesn’t mean fast. Or go for Thunderbolt.. Every Thunderbolt CFexpress reader I have personally tested and I think I have them all has worked very well and are faster than all of even the fastest of 20Gbps USB 3.2x2 readers I have used ( including our own) .  The Blackjet Thunderbolt reader that looks like it’s straight out of the 90s has been the most reliable for me at least personally and it is lighting fast.  OWC has a new thunderbolt reader that I have just started using that has a weird speed ramp-up for me for a second or two but once it is going it is the fastest of any reader I have used ( at least for me on a M2 Mac Studio Ultra ) And the Sabrent thunderbolt reader is almost as fast but also seems to be the most well built.. I’d feel ok about It if I ran over it with a tank.  Anyways… punchline… if you can, avoid a reader that says 10Gbps unless you are ok with riding the slow train.  And avoid the cheap readers and cheap cables. 
And back to that new M2 Mac Studio many of you are just starting to receive.. if you don’t have the Ultra version of the M2 studio unfortunately those front ports that look like thunderbolt are not thunderbolt and sadly even worse are the slow version of USB 3.  So use the ports on the back.

Done!  The last Stormtrooper K-X has been assembled, tested and delivered. The machine in this photo is probably the least critical of all the machines in the process… it’s just the shrink wrap chamber… but to me it’s the most important and which is why I call it the incubator. It is the final step in a very long journey and that shhhwoop is just such a satisfying sound to finish an incredible process. This photo is of the actual final stormtrooper that was assembled at our HQ in California and was shipped to Scott Balkum yesterday. Scott being the final customer was totally unplanned, but very fitting nevertheless. Scott does so much for the community and I’m honored to call a friend so I’m stoked he got to be the surprise cherry on top of this whole crazy adventure.  And now the machines are turned over to making black K-X cameras and those should start to show up within the week in small numbers, with a quick big big ramp up next week.  Thank you to all you stormtrooper customers out there, your feedback and testing benefits every customer and every black customer in the next few months should raise a glass to you all, as the first black cameras will be shipped with a fresh out of the oven release firmware that is the result of all the banging and breaking  that you ST customers have done over the last few months.  Stormtrooper KX will join the release fork build in a couple weeks and then all KXs live along side by side sharing firmware builds for the rest of time.

Happy National Camera Day!

We obviously really really like this day and have it circled on the calendar every year but in reality, every day is Camera Day to all of us at RED. So today, I want to celebrate something more important— all of the incredible hands that hold the cameras.

For nearly two centuries since the invention of the camera, technology has continued to propel the quality of imaging to new heights. Throughout that time, one constant has remained unchanged: the unmatched vision of storytellers and the indispensable role of the operators behind these tools.

So today, we at RED celebrate all the photographers and cinematographers, the wielders of the magical record trigger. Because no matter how far technology advances, and no matter how hard technology tries, a camera without an artist's vision remains utterly blind to both authentic reality and reality forged.
